Dragon Ball Supervised Learning Regression¶

Problem Definition¶

"Can we accurately predict a Dragon Ball character's power level based on their race, transformations, combat skills, and abilities?"

Context¶

  • In the Dragon Ball universe, a character’s power level is a key indicator of their strength and battle potential.
  • By using machine learning regression, we can estimate power levels based on different factors like transformations, combat abilities, and species traits.
  • This could be useful for game balancing, fan discussions, and AI-generated character rankings.

Objective¶

  • Build a regression model to predict Power Level based on selected attributes.
  • Identify key features that contribute the most to power level estimation.
  • Analyze patterns in how different races, transformations, and fighting styles impact power levels.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Name: Character's name
  • Race: The species of the fighter (Saiyan, Namekian, etc.)
  • Gender: Male or Female
  • Power Level: The numeric power level (Target Variable)
    • Y Variable (Target)
  • Ki Blast: Character’s energy attack technique
  • Melee Combat: Fighting style and close-combat abilities
  • Speed: Speed level (Numeric)
  • Special Attack: Ultimate moves or techniques
  • Transformation: The highest transformation level achieved (Super Saiyan, etc.)
  • Speed_Original: Descriptive speed category (Fast, Medium, Slow)
  • Normalized_Power: Scaled power level (0-1)
  • Power_Score: Normalized score based on battle metrics
  • Meta: Combined metadata of character attributes

  • Melee Combat Techniques:

    • Android Strikes and Martial Arts appear more often, suggesting their general effectiveness.
    • Many techniques are unique or used by only a few characters.

Observations

  • Most characters have no recorded transformation (indicated by "-" as the highest bar).

    • This suggests many characters either lack transformation abilities or their transformations are not explicitly listed.

  • Super Saiyan is the most frequent transformation among named forms.

    • This aligns with Saiyans being dominant combatants.

  • Other transformations like "Merge with Piccolo", "Super Saiyan 2", and "Perfect Form" are much rarer.

    • This suggests these abilities are specialized or unique to a few characters.

  • Final Form, Various Forms, and Absorption are minimally represented, likely tied to very specific races (e.g., Frieza’s race or Majins).

Insights

  • Saiyans and Humans dominate the dataset, with Androids following closely.
  • Kamehameha is the most common Ki Blast, reflecting its prominence in the Dragon Ball universe.
  • Many characters do not have transformations, but when present, Super Saiyan is the most frequent one.
  • There is a long tail distribution in special attacks and transformations, with most being unique to a few characters.

sns.histplot(x = 'Normalized_Power', data = data, kde = True, ax = axes[1,0]);

sns.histplot(x = 'Power_Score', data = data, kde = True, ax = axes[1,1]);

plt.tight_layout()

Observations

  • Power Level Distribution (Top-Left)

    • Highly right-skewed distribution: Most characters have low power levels, while only a few possess extremely high power levels.
    • A few outliers: Some characters exceed 100,000+ power levels, making them stand out significantly from the rest.

  • Speed Distribution (Top-Right)

    • Three distinct speed categories: The dataset mainly contains speeds of 1, 2, and 3, suggesting a categorical-like distribution.
    • Most characters have either speed 1 or 3, while speed 2 is less common.

  • Normalized Power Distribution (Bottom-Left)

    • Similar pattern to Power Level: Most characters have low normalized power, with very few reaching values near 1.0.
    • Extreme imbalance: The majority of values cluster near 0.0, suggesting that very few characters possess exceptional power.

  • Power Score Distribution (Bottom-Right)

    • Bimodal distribution: There are two peaks, one around 0.4 and another around 1.0.
    • Most characters have low power scores, but there is still a subset with significantly higher values.
    • Some extreme values exist around 1.5+, indicating very powerful characters.

Insights

  • Power levels and normalized power are heavily skewed, meaning most characters have relatively low power, while a few outliers dominate.
  • Speed is likely categorical, as it only takes a few distinct values (1, 2, 3).
  • The power score shows two peaks, indicating two broad groups of characters – weaker and stronger ones.
  • Outliers exist, meaning power-related features might need transformation (e.g., log scaling) to improve modeling performance.

Correlations

In [669]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12, 4))

sns.heatmap(data.corr(numeric_only=True), annot = True, mask=mask);

plt.xticks(rotation = 45);

Observations

  • Power Level

    • Strong correlation with Power Score (0.63):
      • Higher power levels tend to result in higher power scores.
      • This suggests that Power Level is a key predictor of Power Score.

  • Speed

    • Moderate correlation with Normalized Power (0.32):
      • Faster characters tend to have slightly higher normalized power but not always.
    • High correlation with Power Score (0.93):
      • Speed and Power Score are highly correlated, meaning faster characters are often ranked stronger.
      • This suggests that speed is an important factor in ranking character strength.

  • Normalized Power

    • Perfect correlation with itself (1.0), which is expected.
    • Strong correlation with Power Score (0.63):
      • This implies that Normalized Power is closely linked to Power Score, but it is not the only factor.

Insights

  • Power Level and Power Score are strongly related, meaning stronger characters tend to score higher.
  • Speed is highly correlated with Power Score, suggesting fast characters are often perceived as more powerful.
  • Normalized Power is an important predictor of Power Score, but other factors likely play a role too.
  • Speed does not have a strong link to Power Level, meaning strength and agility are somewhat independent traits in this dataset.

Observations

  • Normalized Power vs. Power Level (Middle Plot)
    • Strong positive correlation: Higher normalized power is associated with higher power levels.
    • Most data points cluster near the lower end, meaning a majority of characters have low power levels, but a few extreme cases exist.
    • A few outliers at the top suggest that some characters with high power levels also have the highest normalized power.
  • Power Score vs. Power Level (Right Plot)
    • Strong positive correlation: As power level increases, power score also increases.
    • Non-linear trend: Power score increases significantly for higher power levels, indicating a possible exponential relationship.
    • This confirms Power Score is a strong predictor of Power Level

Insights

  • Speed has little impact on Power Level, meaning strength does not always depend on agility.
  • Normalized Power and Power Score both have strong positive correlations with Power Level, confirming their importance as predictors.
  • The relationship between Power Level and Power Score appears non-linear, possibly requiring log transformation or polynomial regression for better predictions.

Scaling¶

Scaling Options

In [677]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import (
    StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler, RobustScaler, MaxAbsScaler,
    PowerTransformer, QuantileTransformer, Normalizer
)

# 📌 Load dataset (Modify path if needed)
#file_path = "your_dataset.csv"  # Update with correct file
#data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# 📌 Select numeric columns only
numeric_features = train_features.select_dtypes(include=['number']).dropna()

# 📌 Detect Outliers using IQR (Interquartile Range)
def detect_outliers(df):
    outlier_info = {}
    for column in df.columns:
        Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Count outliers
        outlier_count = ((df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)).sum()
        outlier_info[column] = outlier_count

    return outlier_info

outliers = detect_outliers(numeric_features)
outlier_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(outliers, orient='index', columns=['Outlier Count'])

# 📌 Check Skewness (to determine if transformation is needed)
skewness = numeric_features.skew()

# 📌 Scaling Options with All Variants
scalers = {
    "StandardScaler": StandardScaler(),
    "MinMaxScaler": MinMaxScaler(),
    "RobustScaler": RobustScaler(),
    "MaxAbsScaler": MaxAbsScaler(),
    "PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson)": PowerTransformer(method="yeo-johnson"),
    "PowerTransformer (Box-Cox)": PowerTransformer(method="box-cox"),
    "QuantileTransformer (Normal)": QuantileTransformer(output_distribution="normal"),
    "QuantileTransformer (Uniform)": QuantileTransformer(output_distribution="uniform"),
    "Normalizer (L1)": Normalizer(norm="l1"),
    "Normalizer (L2)": Normalizer(norm="l2"),
    "Normalizer (Max)": Normalizer(norm="max"),
}

scaler_results = {}

# 📌 Try all scalers & transformations
for scaler_name, scaler in scalers.items():
    try:
        transformed_data = scaler.fit_transform(numeric_features)
        transformed_df = pd.DataFrame(transformed_data, columns=numeric_features.columns, index=numeric_features.index)

        # Calculate variance after scaling (Higher is better)
        cumulative_variance = transformed_df.var().sum()
        scaler_results[scaler_name] = cumulative_variance

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Error with {scaler_name}: {e}")

# 📌 Convert results to DataFrame and Rank
scaler_rank_df = pd.DataFrame(list(scaler_results.items()), columns=['Scaler', 'Cumulative Variance'])
scaler_rank_df = scaler_rank_df.sort_values(by="Cumulative Variance", ascending=False)

# 📌 Pick the best scaler based on variance ranking
best_scaler_name = scaler_rank_df.iloc[0]["Scaler"]
best_scaler = scalers[best_scaler_name]
scaled_data = best_scaler.fit_transform(numeric_features)

# 📌 Convert Scaled Data to DataFrame
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled_data, columns=numeric_features.columns, index=numeric_features.index)

# 📌 Save the scaled dataset
scaled_df.to_csv("scaled_dataset.csv", index=False)

# 📌 Explain Selection
explanations = {
    "MinMaxScaler": "Scales data between [0,1]. Used in Unsupervised Learning & Deep Learning but NOT recommended for outliers.",
    "StandardScaler": "Standardizes data to mean=0, variance=1. Recommended for Unsupervised Learning & Deep Learning. Works well with outliers.",
    "RobustScaler": "Uses median and IQR. Best choice for handling outliers in both Unsupervised and Supervised Learning.",
    "MaxAbsScaler": "Scales data between [-1,1]. Used for sparse data, not generally needed for typical datasets.",
    "PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson)": "Transforms data to be more Gaussian-like. Good for skewed data in Regression & Classification.",
    "PowerTransformer (Box-Cox)": "Similar to Yeo-Johnson but works only with strictly positive values. Reduces skewness.",
    "QuantileTransformer (Normal)": "Maps data to a normal distribution. Works well when distribution is unknown.",
    "QuantileTransformer (Uniform)": "Maps data to a uniform distribution. Useful for highly irregular distributions.",
    "Normalizer (L1)": "Normalizes each row by L1 norm. Good for text-based or sparse datasets.",
    "Normalizer (L2)": "Normalizes each row by L2 norm. Often used in clustering tasks.",
    "Normalizer (Max)": "Normalizes each row by its maximum absolute value. Good for text and sparse data."
}

# 📌 Print Summary
print("\n📊 Scaler Rankings:")
print(scaler_rank_df)

print(f"\n🏆 Best Scaler Chosen: {best_scaler_name}")
print(f"📌 Reason: {explanations.get(best_scaler_name, 'No explanation available')}")

# 📌 Print Insights
if outlier_df['Outlier Count'].sum() > 0:
    print("\n⚠️ Outliers detected! **RobustScaler** is recommended if handling them is critical.")
else:
    print("\n✅ No significant outliers detected. **StandardScaler** is the default recommendation.")

if any(abs(skewness) > 1):
    print("\n⚠️ Skewed data detected! **PowerTransformer**")

❌ Error with PowerTransformer (Box-Cox): The Box-Cox transformation can only be applied to strictly positive data

⚠️ Skewed data detected! **PowerTransformer**

MinMaxScaler

  • Data with a fixed range (0 to 1)
  • Does not handle outliers

RobustScaler

  • Data with outliers & skewed distributions
  • Handles skew and outliers well

Build the Model¶

Set to build the model using the statsmodels package

In [680]:
# Importing libraries for building linear regression model
import statsmodels.api as sm # advantage of scick learn when training linear regression models: we can have summary of model regression
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
In [681]:
# Adding the intercept term
train_features_scaled = sm.add_constant(train_features_scaled)

# call the OLS algorithm on the train features and the target variable
ols_model_0 = sm.OLS(train_target, train_features_scaled)

# Fitting the model
ols_res_0 = ols_model_0.fit()

print(ols_res_0.summary())

  • F-statistic: Lets you compare models in their ability to "explain" the variance in the dependent variable. More information here.

  • Log-likelihood. Measure the goodness of fit for a model. The higher the value of the log-likelihood, the better a model fits a dataset.

  • AIC and BIC are methods to compare models and determine which one is the best fit for the data.

    • Akaike Information Criterion (AIC): It uses the maximum likelihood and the number of independent variables in the model. Simply choose the model giving smallest AIC. More information here.
    • Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC): Unlike the AIC, the BIC penalizes the model more for its complexity, meaning that more complex models will have a worse (larger) score and will, in turn, be less likely to be selected. More information here.

  • Omnibus/Prob(Omnibus): The Prob (Omnibus) performs a statistical test indicating the probability that the residuals are normally distributed.

  • Skew: A measure of data symmetry. We want to see something close to zero, indicating the residual distribution is normal.

  • Kurtosis: A measure of "peakiness", or curvature of the data.

  • Durbin-Watson: Tests for homoscedasticity. We hope to have a value between 1 and 2.

  • Jarque-Bera (JB)/Prob(JB): Like the Omnibus test in that it tests both skew and kurtosis.

  • Condition Number: This test measures the sensitivity of a function's output as compared to its input. If the value is greater to 30, we have multicollinearity.

Removing Multicollinearity¶

  • Multicollinearity occurs when predictor variables in a regression model are correlated. This correlation is a problem because predictor variables should be independent. If the correlation between independent variables is high, it can cause problems when we fit the model and interpret the results. When we have multicollinearity in the linear model, the coefficients that the model suggests are unreliable.

    • Correlation measures the strength and direction of the relationship between two variables.
    • The correlation coefficient, denoted as r, ranges from -1 to 1.

  • r ≈ 1:

    • This indicates a strong positive correlation, meaning as one variable increases, the other also increases in a very predictable way

  • r ≈ −1:

    • This indicates a strong negative correlation, meaning as one variable increases, the other decreases in a very predictable way.

  • There are different ways of detecting (or testing) multicollinearity. One such way is the Variation Inflation Factor (VIF) or pearson correlation coefficient

  • Variance Inflation factor: Variance inflation factor measures the inflation in the variances of the regression parameter estimates due to collinearities that exist among the predictors. It is a measure of how much the variance of the estimated regression coefficient βk is “inflated” by the existence of correlation among the predictor variables in the model.

  • General Rule of thumb: If VIF is 1, then there is no correlation between the kth predictor and the remaining predictor variables, and hence the variance of β̂k is not inflated at all. Whereas, if VIF exceeds 5 or is close to exceeding 5, we say there is moderate VIF and if it is 10 or exceeds 10, it shows signs of high multicollinearity.

General Rule of thumb:

  • If VIF is 1, then there is no correlation between the kth predictor and the remaining predictor variables,
  • and hence the variance of β̂k is not inflated at all. Whereas, if VIF exceeds 5 or is close to exceeding 5, we say there is moderate VIF
  • and if it is 10 or exceeds 10, it shows signs of high multicollinearity.

Define Function to Remove High P-Values and High VIF

Original Model: ols_res_0

In [682]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
import statsmodels.api as sm

def remove_high_pvalues_vif(feature_data, target_data, pvalue_threshold=0.05, vif_threshold=10):
    """
    Iteratively removes features with high p-values and high VIF.

    Parameters:
    - feature_data: DataFrame containing features used in the model.
    - target_data: Series or array containing the target variable.
    - pvalue_threshold: The threshold for p-values to retain a feature (default = 0.05).
    - vif_threshold: The threshold for Variance Inflation Factor (default = 10).

    Returns:
    - final_features: List of remaining features after filtering.
    - removed_pvalues: List of removed features due to high p-values.
    - removed_vif: List of removed features due to high VIF.
    """

    # Ensure consistent index alignment
    feature_data = feature_data.reset_index(drop=True)
    target_data = target_data.reset_index(drop=True)

    # Start with all features
    remaining_features = feature_data.columns.tolist()
    removed_pvalues, removed_vif = [], []

    iteration = 1

    while True:
        print(f"\n🔄 **Iteration {iteration}: Running P-Value and VIF Analysis**")

        # Fit OLS model
        X = sm.add_constant(feature_data[remaining_features])
        model = sm.OLS(target_data, X).fit()

        # Extract and format p-values
        pvalues = model.pvalues[1:].apply(lambda x: round(x, 2))  # Format as xx.xx

        # Compute VIF values
        vif_values = pd.Series(
            [variance_inflation_factor(X[remaining_features].values, i) for i in range(len(remaining_features))],
            index=remaining_features
        )

        # Display results
        results_table = pd.DataFrame({"Feature": remaining_features, "P-Value": pvalues, "VIF": vif_values})
        print(results_table)

        # Identify max p-value and max VIF
        max_pvalue = pvalues.max()
        max_vif = vif_values.max()

        if max_pvalue < pvalue_threshold and max_vif < vif_threshold:
            print("\n✅ **All Features Meet Criteria! Stopping Iterations.**")
            break  # Stop if all conditions are met

        # Remove highest p-value if above threshold
        if max_pvalue >= pvalue_threshold:
            feature_to_remove = pvalues.idxmax()
            print(f"\n🚨 **Removing Feature (High P-Value):** {feature_to_remove} | P-Value: {max_pvalue:.2f}")
            remaining_features.remove(feature_to_remove)
            removed_pvalues.append(feature_to_remove)

        # Remove highest VIF if above threshold
        elif max_vif >= vif_threshold:
            feature_to_remove = vif_values.idxmax()
            print(f"\n🚨 **Removing Feature (High VIF):** {feature_to_remove} | VIF: {max_vif:.2f}")
            remaining_features.remove(feature_to_remove)
            removed_vif.append(feature_to_remove)

        iteration += 1

    return remaining_features, removed_pvalues, removed_vif

remaining_features, removed_pvalues, removed_vif = remove_high_pvalues_vif(
    train_features_scaled_new, train_target, pvalue_threshold=0.05, vif_threshold=10
)

# Display final feature selection results
print("\n✅ **Final Remaining Features After P-Value & VIF Filtering:**")
print(remaining_features)

print("\n🚫 **Removed Due to High P-Value:**")
print(removed_pvalues)

print("\n🚫 **Removed Due to High VIF:**")
print(removed_vif)

    [variance_inflation_factor(X_final[remaining_features].values, i) for i in range(len(remaining_features))],
    index=remaining_features
)

print("\n🔎 **Final Validation Check:**")

if (final_pvalues > 0.05).sum() == 0 and all(vif < 10 for vif in final_vif_values):

Mean of residuals should be 0¶

In [689]:
# Residuals Calculation
# Use the most recent model (new_model_after_vif_analysis)
residual = final_model.resid

# Calculate the mean of residuals
residual_mean = residual.mean()
print(f"Mean of Residuals: {residual_mean}")

# Interpretation
if abs(residual_mean) < 1e-10:  # Adjust the tolerance as needed
    print("\nThe mean of residuals is very close to 0. Hence, the corresponding assumption is satisfied.")
else:
    print("\nThe mean of residuals is not close to 0. The assumption may not be satisfied.")

Mean of Residuals: 1.669190276195021e-11

The mean of residuals is very close to 0. Hence, the corresponding assumption is satisfied.

Tests for Normality¶

  • Error terms/Residuals should be normally distributed.
  • If the error terms are non-normally distributed, confidence intervals may become too wide or narrow. Once the confidence interval becomes unstable, it leads to difficulty in estimating coefficients based on the minimization of least squares.
  • It suggests that there are a few unusual data points that must be studied closely to make a better model.

How to check the normality

  • We can plot the histogram of residuals and check the distribution visually.
  • It can be checked via QQ Plot. Residuals following normal distribution will make a straight line plot otherwise not.
  • Another test to check for normality: The Shapiro-Wilk test.

Fix

  • apply transformations like log, exponential, arcsinh, etc. as per our data
In [690]:
# Plot histogram of residuals with KDE (Kernel Density Estimate)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(residual, kde=True, color="blue")
plt.title("Histogram of Residuals (New Model)", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Residuals", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=14)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Residual Distribution:

  • The histogram shows that most residuals are clustered around zero, which is ideal.
  • The kernel density estimate (KDE) line suggests a somewhat normal distribution, but there are visible deviations.

Outliers & Skewness:

  • There are a few extreme residuals on both the negative and positive sides, indicating possible outliers.
  • The right tail (positive residuals) extends further, suggesting a potential right-skewed distribution.

Linearity of Variables¶

  • states that the predictor variables must have a linear relation with the dependent variable
  • plot the residuals and the fitted values and ensure that residuals do not form a strong pattern. They should be randomly and uniformly scattered on the x-axis
In [691]:
# Predicted (fitted) values and residuals from the newest model
fitted = final_model.fittedvalues

# Residual plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.residplot(x=fitted, y=residual, color="lightblue", lowess=True)
plt.xlabel("Fitted Values", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Residuals", fontsize=14)
plt.title("Residual Plot (Linearity of Variables)", fontsize=16)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
  • Linearity Check:
    • Ideally, residuals should be randomly scattered around zero with no clear pattern.
    • The residuals mostly hover around zero, but there are some deviations, especially at lower fitted values.
  • Outliers & Influential Points:
    • Several large residuals (positive and negative) indicate potential outliers.
    • These could bias model predictions and should be further examined using Cook’s Distance or Leverage Plots.
  • Lowess (Locally Weighted Regression) Curve:
    • The blue Lowess curve slightly deviates from zero in the lower fitted values.
    • This suggests a possible non-linearity in the data that the model isn’t capturing well.

Implement Fix

  • apply the log transformation on the target variable and try to build a new model.
In [692]:
# Log transformation on the target variable for the new model
train_target_log = np.log(train_target)

# Fitting new model with the transformed target variable
final_model = sm.OLS(train_target_log, train_features_scaled_new)

final_model = final_model.fit()
In [693]:
# Fitting new model with the transformed target variable
final_model = sm.OLS(train_target_log, train_features_scaled_new)

final_model = final_model.fit()
In [694]:
# Predicted values
fitted = final_model.fittedvalues

residual1 = final_model.resid

sns.residplot(x = fitted, y = residual1, color = "lightblue")

plt.xlabel("Fitted Values")

plt.ylabel("Residual")

plt.title("Residual PLOT")

plt.show()

  • Log Transformation Applied:

    • The target variable (train_target) was transformed using the natural logarithm (np.log(train_target)).
    • This transformation helps to stabilize variance, make relationships more linear, and improve model performance.

  • Fitting the Log-Transformed Model:

    • The model (final_model) was trained using the transformed target (train_target_log).
    • This approach often improves regression assumptions like normality and homoscedasticity of residuals.

  • Residual Plot Analysis:

    • The residuals are centered around zero, which is a good sign.
    • However, there are a few outliers with larger residuals.
    • Most residuals are tightly clustered near zero, indicating the model captures the majority of variation well.
In [695]:
# print(final_model.summary())

No Heteroscedasticity¶

Test for Homoscedasticity

  • Homoscedasticity - If the variance of the residuals are symmetrically distributed across the regression line, then the data is said to homoscedastic.
  • Heteroscedasticity - If the variance is unequal for the residuals across the regression line, then the data is said to be heteroscedastic. In this case, the residuals can form an arrow shape or any other non symmetrical shape.
  • We will use Goldfeld–Quandt test to check homoscedasticity.
    • Null hypothesis : Residuals are homoscedastic
    • Alternate hypothesis : Residuals are hetroscedastic
In [696]:
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip

name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]

test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(train_target_log, train_features_scaled_new)

lzip(name, test)
Out[696]:
[('F statistic', 0.6564517451301212), ('p-value', 0.5668343085677284)]

  • Test Explanation:

    • The Goldfeld-Quandt test checks for heteroscedasticity (unequal variance in residuals).
    • Null hypothesis (H₀): Residuals are homoscedastic (equal variance).
    • Alternative hypothesis (H₁): Residuals are heteroscedastic (unequal variance).

  • Results Interpretation:

    • F-statistic = 0.6564 (lower values generally suggest homoscedasticity).
    • P-value = 0.5668 (greater than 0.05, meaning we fail to reject the null hypothesis).
    • Since p > 0.05, the test does not provide evidence of heteroscedasticity.

  • Conclusion:

    • The residual variance appears uniformly distributed across fitted values.
    • The assumption of homoscedasticity is satisfied, which supports the validity of regression estimates.

Evaluation Metrics¶

R-Squared

  • The R-squared metric gives us an indication that how good/bad our model is from a baseline model
In [697]:
print(final_model.rsquared)

0.985862004163971

Mean Squared Error

  • This metric measures the average of the squares of the errors, i.e., the average squared difference between the estimated values and the actual value.
In [698]:
print(final_model.mse_resid)

0.808999699008203

Root Mean Squared Error

  • This metric is the same as the above but, instead of simply taking the average, we also take the square root of MSE to get RMSE.
  • This helps to get the metric in the same unit as the target variable.
In [699]:
print(np.sqrt(final_model.mse_resid))

0.8994441055497573

Checking the cross-validation score to identify if the model that we have built is underfitted, overfitted or just right fit model.

In [700]:
# Fitting linear model

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

linearregression = LinearRegression()

cv_Score11 = cross_val_score(linearregression, train_features_scaled_new, train_target_log, cv = 10) # 10 is fold iterations

cv_Score12 = cross_val_score(linearregression, train_features_scaled_new, train_target_log, cv = 10,
                             scoring = 'neg_mean_squared_error')

print("RSquared: %0.3f (+/- %0.3f)" % (cv_Score11.mean(), cv_Score11.std()*2))

print("Mean Squared Error: %0.3f (+/- %0.3f)" % (-1*cv_Score12.mean(), cv_Score12.std()*2))

RSquared: -5.031 (+/- 20.480)
Mean Squared Error: 9.245 (+/- 17.415)

Observations

  • Evaluation Metrics

    • R-Squared (0.986): This suggests that 98.6% of the variance in the target variable is explained by the model, which is a strong indication of good model fit.
    • Mean Squared Error (MSE: 0.88) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE: 0.89): These values suggest a small error margin, indicating good prediction accuracy.

  • Cross-Validation Performance

    • R-Squared (-5.03 ± 20.48): A negative R² indicates that the model performs worse than a simple mean-based prediction. The large standard deviation suggests significant variance across folds, indicating instability.
    • Mean Squared Error (9.25 ± 17.41): The high error and large standard deviation suggest that the model does not generalize well across different data splits.

  • Key Takeaways

    • Potential Overfitting: The model performs well on training data (high R²) but performs poorly in cross-validation, suggesting overfitting.

In [741]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (12, 6))

sns.histplot(test_predictions, ax = ax[0]);

sns.histplot(test_predictions_inverse_transformed, ax = ax[1]);

Observations

  • Left Plot (Test Predictions - Log Scale)
    • The values are centered around zero but have negative values, indicating that some predictions are in the negative range.
    • A few outliers exist on the extreme left and right, which may cause instability when exponentiating.
  • Right Plot (Inverse Transformed Predictions - Exponential Scale)
    • The distribution is highly skewed.
    • Most values are clustered at a low range.
    • A few extreme values (possibly from large exponentiation effects) dominate, leading to unrealistic results.

Conclusion¶

  • Model Performance:

    • The final regression model achieved a high R-squared value, indicating a strong fit to the training data.
    • However, the model might be overfitting, as the R² is very high (close to 1), suggesting it captures training data too well but may not generalize well to new data​

  • Multicollinearity Issues:

    • There is evidence of multicollinearity (high correlation between predictor variables), which can distort coefficient estimates and make the model unreliable.
    • Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) analysis should be performed to identify and remove highly correlated features​

  • Feature Selection & Importance:

    • Some variables (e.g., Speed, Ki Blasts, and Melee Attacks) showed minimal impact on predictions and should be considered for removal.
    • Other features, such as Transformations (Super Saiyan, Various Forms), and - - Angel Race, had strong positive effects on the target variable​

  • Model Assumptions & Residuals:

    • The residual plot shows some deviations from normality, suggesting potential non-linearity in the relationships.
    • There were outliers and heteroscedasticity issues that may affect prediction accuracy​

  • Log Transformation Applied:

    • The target variable was log-transformed to improve normality and stabilize variance, improving the model assumptions​
    • However, the inverse transformation led to extreme values (inf values), indicating numerical instability in some cases​

Conclusion

  • Address Overfitting:

    • Reduce the number of features by selecting only the most important ones using p-value filtering (e.g., dropping features with p > 0.05)​
    • Consider using regularization techniques (Lasso/Ridge Regression) to penalize unnecessary complexity​

  • Fix Multicollinearity:

    • Perform VIF analysis and remove highly correlated predictors to improve model reliability​

  • Handle Outliers & Improve Normality:

    • Use Box-Cox or Yeo-Johnson transformations to stabilize variance​
    • Investigate extreme residuals to determine if they should be removed or addressed differently.

  • Improve Feature Engineering:

    • Consider deriving new interaction terms or transforming features that better capture relationships​
    • Normalize or standardize features before applying transformations.

  • Reassess Log Transformation:

    • While the log transformation improved normality, its inverse transformation led to instability.
    • Try alternative transformations (e.g., root transformations) or consider using a different regression approach​

  • Evaluate Model on New Data:

    • Test the model on a validation dataset to confirm if improvements generalize well.
    • Use metrics like Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) to evaluate predictive performance.
